2026-05-17 | Jump Game Reach Zero

Question
Return true if reaching value 0 is possible.
	Key Insight
This is a graph traversal problem:
- each index = node  
- jumps = edges  
So:
		use BFS or DFS.
Need visited array to avoid infinite loops.
	Approach
1.	Use queue for BFS  
2.	Start from given index  
3.	For current index:
		if arr[idx] == 0:
				return true  
4.	Try both jumps:
		idx + arr[idx]
		idx - arr[idx]
5.	If valid and unvisited:
		push into queue
6.	If traversal ends:
		return false
	Time Complexity
	O(n)
	Space Complexity
	O(n)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    bool canReach(vector<int>& arr, int start) {
        int n = arr.size();
        vector<bool> vis(n, false);
        queue<int> q;
        q.push(start);
        vis[start] = true;
        while(!q.empty()){
            int idx = q.front();
            q.pop();
            if(arr[idx] == 0)
                return true;
            int next1 = idx + arr[idx];
            int next2 = idx - arr[idx];
            if(next1 >= 0 && next1 < n && !vis[next1]){
                vis[next1] = true;
                q.push(next1);
            }
            if(next2 >= 0 && next2 < n && !vis[next2]){
                vis[next2] = true;
                q.push(next2);
            }
        }
        return false;
    }
};
	Key Insight
The array naturally forms a graph of reachable indices.  
BFS/DFS explores all possible jumps efficiently
while avoiding revisiting states.
